"Hi, I can confirm this with IPython, but it does not appear in the normal Python interpreter. Also, it does not appear when the function is a lambda, only when it is a real function.\n\nMinimal code:\r\n```\r\nfrom iminuit import Minuit\r\ndef f(x): return x** 2\r\nMinuit(f)\r\n```\n\nI think this is a bug in `warnings` or in `IPython`.\n\nI did some reading how the `warnings` module works. Whenever a warning is raised, the warning is formatted with the standard implementation of this function.\r\n`warnings.formatwarning(message, category, filename, lineno[, line])`\r\nSee https://docs.python.org/2/library/warnings.html#warnings.formatwarning\r\nWhen `line` is not given (which we don't do), it uses the line specified by filename and lineno.\r\n\r\nWe call `warn` from Cython, and it gets confused. It uses the IPython instance as filename, and some lineno which seems arbitrary (it is certainly not the line where `warn` was called in _libiminuit.pyx`). In my case, it is lineno 4. Since IPython is a script with the content\r\n```\r\n#!/usr/bin/python\r\n\r\n# -*- coding: utf-8 -*-\r\nimport re\r\nimport sys\r\n\r\nfrom IPython import start_ipython\r\n\r\nif __name__ == '__main__':\r\n    sys.argv[0] = re.sub(r'(-script\\.pyw|\\.exe)?$', '', sys.argv[0])\r\n    sys.exit(start_ipython())\r\n```\r\nLine number 4 is just `import re`. Now we know at least where it comes from.\n\n@HDembinski - Thanks for figuring this out.\r\n\r\nIf I understand correctly in #233 you monkey-patch  `warnings.formatwarning`.\r\nThis fixes the issue, but it probably also leads to the side effect that just `import iminuit` might lead to changes in warnings formatting and head-scratching for others.\r\n\r\nI found only one post on this issue, proposing a different hack:\r\nhttps://stackoverflow.com/questions/2647128/emitting-cythonic-warnings\r\n\r\nAsk on the Cython mailing list for advice / how others have handled the issue?\n\n@cdeil If you don't like my solution, could you take over then? I already spend a good deal of time figuring out what is going on. I agree that there must be a better solution, this one may have side effects, just like you said.\n\nI've asked on https://groups.google.com/forum/#!forum/cython-users\r\nI think the mailing list is moderator approved, but the message should appear soon.\r\nLet's wait a few days for answers there and then decide what change to make in iminuit.\n\nI think the answer given in https://stackoverflow.com/questions/2647128/emitting-cythonic-warnings\r\ncould work for us, that you found. I will give it a quick try. The solution in this case has no side effects, as far as I can see. In any case, the problem is in Cython and we can only work around it.\r\n\r\n\n\nhttps://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/cython-users/hLNi1y4-Htg\n\nThank you for the comprehensive posting, this looks great. I hope we get a reply.\n\nThis also seems related: https://github.com/cython/cython/issues/1755\r\nThe stack frames in Cython are faked, but only when an exception is raised. This is not done when a warning is raised, which is why warnings behave so strangely.\n\n@HDembinski - See https://github.com/ipython/ipython/issues/11188 and\r\nhttps://groups.google.com/forum/#!topic/cython-users/hLNi1y4-Htg\r\n\r\nMy suggestion would be to just wait and see if / what changes are made in ipython or Cython, and only if the problem is still there say in a month or two, make a change in iminuit.\r\n\n\nOk, I tried to play around with the code a bit and found no solution. I will wait.\n\nRemoving v1.3 milestone. It's been like this for years and no user complained.\r\nProbably this issue will be resolved within the next months by the iminuit or Cython folks.\r\n"